UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2226
1 placements and admissions into medical school in Kentucky, these efforts have not been
2 nearly enough to meet the need; and
3 WHEREAS, greater efforts could be taken to encourage medical school graduates
4 to complete their residencies in medically underserved areas so they might be compelled
5 to continue practicing medicine and living there; and
6 WHEREAS, opportunities to expand health care access in medically underserved
7 areas may include health care workforce diversification, innovative technology-enabled
8 solutions and support, and attention to non-clinical health care needs and community-
9 based care;
10 NOW, THEREFORE,
11 Be it resolved by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
12 Section 1. (1) The General Assembly directs the University of Kentucky,
13 the University of Louisville, and Eastern Kentucky University to coordinate a search for
14 actionable solutions to the physician shortages and to explore and expand health care
15 opportunities in collaboration with community, state agency, professional associations,
16 and other stakeholders. The search to find actionable solutions and explore opportunities
17 to expand health care access shall focus on the:
18 (a) Shortage of primary and specialty care physicians in medically underserved
19 areas;
20 (b) Chronic lack of access to physician care by medically underserved
21 populations;
22 (c) Retaining of physicians in medically underserved areas; and
23 (d) Workforce, technological, and community-based opportunities to increase
24 access to care.
25 (2) The search and exploration shall include an examination of:
26 (a) Current actions being taken;
27 (b) Possibilities for building on current actions; and
Page 2 of 4
BR222600.100 - 2226 - XXXX 3/9/2026 3:25 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2226
1 (c) Innovative actions that may be taken, including but not limited to:
2 1. Sponsorship of community graduate medical education programs;
3 2. Growing graduate medical education sites in medically underserved areas;
4 3. Encouraging safe international physician recruitment;
5 4. Increasing basic administration reimbursement for recruitment and placement
6 services of medical students, residents, and physicians;
7 5. Integrating workforce diversification in educational programs;
8 6. Expanding technological health care delivery options; and
9 7. Considering community-based medical models.
10 (2) The search and exploration shall include an analysis of any existing regulatory
11 or statutory barriers to achieving a solution that attracts providers to medically
12 underserved areas and does not limit modifications or expansions to medical education
13 programs.
14 (3) The University of Kentucky, the University of Louisville, and Eastern
15 Kentucky University shall coordinate to develop a report to be submitted to the General
16 Assembly by January 1, 2027. The report shall:
17 (a) Describe and provide data on medically underserved areas and medically
18 underserved populations by county on the:
19 1. Shortage of primary and specialty care physicians;
20 2. Lack of access to physician care; and
21 3. Retention of physicians;
22 (b) Provide an overview of:
23 1. Current actions;
24 2. Possibilities for building on current actions;
25 3. Innovative actions that may be taken; and
26 4. Regulatory or statutory barriers; and
27 (c) Provide detailed actional solutions and a discussion of opportunities to expand
Page 3 of 4
BR222600.100 - 2226 - XXXX 3/9/2026 3:25 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2226
1 health care opportunities to address the physician shortages in medically underserved
2 areas of Kentucky, including:
3 1. Agencies that may be responsible for the actions;
4 2. Resources needed to achieve the actions; and
5 3. A suggested timeframe for achieving the solutions.
6 Section 2. There is hereby appropriated General Fund moneys in the amount of
7 $250,000 in fiscal year 2026-2027 for the administration and production of the report
8 required under Section 1 of this Act.
9 Section 3. Whereas finding solutions to the shortage of physicians and
10 exploring and expanding health care opportunities in medically underserved areas of the
11 Commonwealth are critically important for the health and well-being of the citizens of
12 this state, an emergency is declared to exist, and this Act takes effect July 1, 2026.
